args: Something's wrong. These fiends'\nnumbers aren't normal!
Ya noticed too? The urn they're carryin'\nis controllin' the fiends.
I heard a distant cry...for JUSTICE!\nMake way for the Karlsplosion, people!
Looks like you're outnumbered, my friends.
Which means it's time I joined the fray!\nPrepare yourselves, fiends!
Everyone, fall in behind him!\nWe'll clear the fiends out first!
Excellent work! That's the last of those!
Next, we strip that urn from the thieves\nand round them up!
Right. Any villains who'd draft an army of\nfiends to do their nefarious bidding\ndeserve a double helping of JUSTICE!
Now's really not the time for introspective\npauses, Karl!
I helped these guys the other day!
They were being attacked by fiends,\nso I made with the justice.
Didn't think the guy who helped us steal\nthis urn would turn around and try to take\nit from us.
Yeah. We tried to buy it off a black market\nfence, but he decided we looked like easy\nmarks and made to gouge us.
Soon as we called the guy out on it,\nhe used the damn thing to sic his pack\nof guard fiends on us.
Karl showed up and took out the fiends.
Which let these jokers steal the urn.
We're proper thankful. This little gem's\nmade all our jobs since go smooth as silk!\nKeh heh ha ha ha!
You're basically an accomplice in all this,\nfriend. Why not just let us go?
I'm not the hero... I'm one of the outlaws?
Ugh. I ain't got time for this!
{player_name}! Back me up!\nWith the fiends gone, the two of us\ncan finish this!
...Whew. One urn confiscated, and one\npack'a thieves trussed up real tight.\nThat's everything sorted.
Well, almost everything. Karl, how ya\nholding up there?
Everything I stood for was a lie...\nMy life is a hollow mockery of justice...
Come now, Karl. We all make mistakes.
It's what we do after that matters.
Waugh?! That was a little sudden!\nAnd exceptionally loud...
You're right. I'll take some time to ponder\nwhat justice truly means to me!\nHa HAA ha ha ha!
Well, at least he's back in high spirits.
I think I liked him better depressed.
